Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Remove — not needed with cooperative model |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` + Abort | Timeout enforcement | `Join(timeout)` after `Cancel()` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — same logic that was in the ThreadAbortException handler
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — cooperative cancellation doesn't rethrow automatically.
                // The loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal the token — replaces Thread.Abort

        // Give the thread time to finish, replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation,
            // you cannot force-kill it. Log a warning — see pitfalls below.
            Console.Error.WriteLine("Warning: worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

1. **`volatile bool` → `CancellationToken`** — The token replaces both the boolean flag *and* the abort mechanism in a single primitive.

2. **`GetNextItem()` must accept a token** — This is the critical pitfall. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a `BlockingCollection` or socket), cancellation won't interrupt it unless the token is threaded through:
   ```csharp
   // Before: blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
   var item = _queue.Take();

   // After: throws OperationCanceledException when token fires
   var item = _queue.Take(token);
   ```

3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removed entirely** — Cooperative cancellation doesn't auto-rethrow. The `catch` runs, then `finally` runs, then the loop condition (`!token.IsCancellationRequested`) exits naturally.

4. **No force-kill equivalent exists** — `Thread.Abort()` has **no replacement** in .NET 8. If the thread ignores the token, `Join` will time out and the thread keeps running. If you have truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and use `Process.Kill()`.

## Common Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| Not passing the token to `GetNextItem()` | The thread stays blocked forever — cancellation never fires |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish cancellation from other failures |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Leaks timers and registered callbacks |
| Expecting cancellation to be instant | It only fires at the next checkpoint — long `ProcessItem()` calls delay shutdown |
